Trump and economy
New York—Financial markets have finally woken up, and it turns out Trump is the President of the United States.
The world has endured this man with the most power in the world for two years, and his unfiltered tweets and public statements are apparent problems. What has kept it going for so long?
On the one hand, until now, investors have been humanely giving Trump a pass, not raining on his parade.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies that are beneficial to the corporate department and shareholders, they will give him the benefit of the doubt.
Many people believed that in the end, "grown-ups in the room" would restrain Trump, ensuring government policies wouldn't go too far.
This assumption was somewhat verified in Trump's first year in office, as the economy grew and corporate profit expectations grew — thanks to impending tax cuts and deregulation — making the stock market stand out.
The US stock index rose by over 20% in 2017.
But in 2018, the situation took a sharp turn, especially in the last few months.
Although corporate profits increased by over 20% (thanks to tax cuts), the US stock market fluctuated for most of the year and then plummeted.
Currently, all indices are located in the correction interval (i.e., 10% below the recent highs) , while the tech stock indices (such as NASDAQ), have fallen into a bear market (decline of 20% or more) .
Although the increasing volatility of the financial markets reflects the concerns about China, Italy and other Eurozone economies, as well as key emerging economies, the recent turmoil is due to Trump.
At the beginning of the year, Trump implemented a reckless tax cut, resulting in the rise of long-term interest rates, and the economy, which had already reached a peak near full employment, surged further.
By February, concerns about inflation rising above the Federal Reserve's target of 2% led to the first wave of risk aversion in 2018.
Then, Trump launched a trade war with China and other important US trading partners.
Markets' concerns over protectionist government policies have fluctuated throughout the year but are now reaching a new peak.
Recent US actions against China seem to be preparing for a full-scale trade, economic, and geopolitics cold war.
Another concern is that other Trump policies may lead to stagflation (growth weakening while inflation increases).
After all, Trump plans to limit foreign direct investment inflows and implement extensive immigration restrictions, which will hinder labor supply growth amid severe labor force aging and skills mismatch issues.
Furthermore, the Trump administration has yet to propose infrastructure plans to stimulate private sector productivity or accelerate green economy transformation.
In Twitter and other occasions, Trump constantly criticizes corporate recruitment, production, investment and pricing behaviors, especially for technology companies, which are now facing widespread opposition and increasingly fierce competition from Chinese rivals.
New emerging markets have been hit by the US policy.
Monetary policy tightening and fiscal stimulus have pushed up short-term and long-term borrowing rates, strengthening the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies face capital flight and appreciation of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies heavily reliant on exports have suffered losses due to the decline in commodity prices, and even countries with indirect trade with China have felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policy also created volatility.
US re-implementation of Iran sanctions drove up oil prices, after which the US government canceled exemptions, threatened Saudi Arabia to raise oil production, causing oil prices to plummet.
Although American consumers benefited from low oil prices, the American energy sector's stock prices couldn't bear it.
In addition, excessive oil price volatility is not beneficial to producers and consumers, as it hinders wise investment and consumption decisions.
Worse still, it is now clear that the benefits of last year's tax cuts have almost all flowed to the corporate sector, and have not taken the form of higher real wages (adjusted for inflation) to the family.
This means that family consumption may slow down soon, further affecting the economy.
However, the recent sharp decline of US and global stock markets is mainly due to Trump's words and actions.
Worse than the prominent risk of a full-scale trade war with China (although he recently made a "ceasefire" agreement with Chinese President Xi Jinping) is Trump's public criticism of the Federal Reserve.
These early criticisms began in the spring of 2018, when the US economic growth rate exceeded 4%.
As a result, the market was alarmed when the Federal Reserve correctly decided to raise interest rates in this month, and hinted that it would raise interest rates more slowly in 2019.
Facing tweets from an antagonistic president, Federal Reserve Chairman Jerome Powell needs to signal that the central bank still maintains its political independence.
But then, because Congress refused to allocate funds for his useless Mexican border wall, Trump decided to partially shut down the federal government.
This move pushed the market into a state of panic, and with the government shutdown, there were soon reports that Trump wanted to fire Powell — which could turn the market correction into a crash.
At the eve of the Christmas holiday, US Secretary of the Treasury Steven Mnuchin was forced to make a public statement to calm the market.
He declared that Trump had no plan to fire Powell, and that the US financial situation was good, which ironically highlighted the question of whether it was really good.
While shifts in government personnel not affecting economic policy decisions still concern the market.
White House Chief of Staff John Kelly and Defense Secretary James Mattis are about to leave, and the Trump cabinet will be without any sane person.
The remaining will be all economic nationalists and hawkish foreign policy officials, only loyal to Trump.
The possibility of a full-scale geographic conflict with China still cannot be ruled out.
A new Cold War is very likely to lead to deglobalization and destroy the global supply chain, but the tech industry will be the first to be hit, and recent cases of ZTE and Huawei are evidence.
While this is happening, Trump seems determined to destroy the cohesion of the European Union and NATO at a time when Europe's economy and politics are unstable.
The investigation by special counsel Robert Mueller into Trump's relationship with Russia during the 2016 campaign is the Damocles' sword hanging over the head of the Trump presidency.
Trump is now the mad scientist of the financial market.
Like the paranoiac in Stanley Kubrick's classic film, he is trapped in a self-fulfilling cycle of economic destruction.
Now, the market has seen this danger, and the risk of a financial crisis and global recession is rising steadily.
